insert into cases (title, category, difficulty, estimated_minutes, amc_exam_type, steps) values
(
  'Chest Pain in a 58-Year-Old Man',
  'Hospital & Emergency',
  'Medium',
  15,
  'CAT 2',
  '[{"step":1,"type":"presentation","title":"Presentation","content":"You are the ED registrar. A 58-year-old man named Robert is brought in by ambulance. He reports crushing central chest pain radiating to his left arm, started 45 minutes ago. He is diaphoretic and pale.\n\nVitals: BP 95/60, HR 110, RR 22, SpO2 95% on air, Temp 37.1°C\n\nWhat is your immediate approach?"},{"step":2,"type":"history","title":"History Taking","content":"You take a focused history. Robert says the pain is 9/10, crushing, with associated nausea. No pleuritic component. No recent travel. He has a history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes. He smokes 20 cigarettes/day. He takes metformin and amlodipine. No known drug allergies.\n\nKey history prompt: What cardiac risk factors does he have, and what differentials are you considering?"},{"step":3,"type":"examination","title":"Examination Findings","content":"On examination:\n- Looks unwell, diaphoretic\n- JVP elevated at 4cm\n- Heart sounds: S3 gallop, no murmur\n- Lung bases: Fine bibasal crepitations\n- Peripheries: Cool, capillary refill 3 seconds\n- No leg swelling\n\n12-lead ECG shows: ST elevation 3mm in leads II, III, aVF. Reciprocal ST depression in I and aVL.\n\nWhat is your diagnosis and what do you do next?"},{"step":4,"type":"investigations","title":"Investigations","content":"Results:\n- Troponin I: 2.8 ng/mL (elevated, ref <0.04)\n- CK-MB: elevated\n- Chest X-ray: Mild pulmonary congestion, normal cardiac silhouette\n- Bloods: Hb 138, WBC 14.2, Cr 102, BSL 14.2\n- Coags: Normal\n\nConfirm your diagnosis. Which management pathway do you activate?"},{"step":5,"type":"management","title":"Management Plan","content":"This is an inferior STEMI with cardiogenic shock. You have a cath lab available and PCI is achievable within 90 minutes.\n\nWrite your immediate management plan. Consider: medications, monitoring, escalation, communication.","model_answer":"1. ACTIVATE cath lab — inferior STEMI, target PCI <90 mins\n2. Dual antiplatelet: Aspirin 300mg + Ticagrelor 180mg stat (loaded)\n3. Anticoagulation: UFH 60 units/kg IV bolus\n4. Oxygen: Maintain SpO2 >94%\n5. IV access x2, continuous cardiac monitoring, 12-lead serial ECGs\n6. Cardiogenic shock: cautious 250ml fluid bolus, may need vasopressors (noradrenaline)\n7. Avoid GTN — hypotensive (SBP 95)\n8. Notify cardiology + ICU early\n9. NBM — may need procedure\n10. Family communication and informed consent for PCI"},{"step":6,"type":"debrief","title":"Debrief & Examiner Tips","content":"Key learning points:\n\n✅ Inferior STEMI: ST elevation in II, III, aVF — always check right-sided leads (V4R) for RV infarction\n✅ Cardiogenic shock complicates ~5-10% of STEMI — avoid aggressive fluids, early vasopressors\n✅ GTN is contraindicated in hypotension and suspected RV infarction\n✅ The AMC examiner looks for: systematic approach, correct diagnosis, PCI activation, medication safety\n\n⚠️ Common mistakes:\n- Giving GTN when BP <100\n- Forgetting to load dual antiplatelet before PCI\n- Not recognising cardiogenic shock pattern\n\nReference: eTG Cardiovascular — STEMI Management (2024)"}]'
),
(
  'Patient Refuses Blood Transfusion',
  'Ethics & Communication',
  'Hard',
  12,
  'CAT 2',
  '[{"step":1,"type":"presentation","title":"Presentation","content":"You are the surgical registrar. Margaret, a 42-year-old Jehovah''s Witness, is admitted with heavy post-partum haemorrhage. Her Hb is 58 g/L and dropping. She is conscious and alert.\n\nShe firmly states: ''I will not accept blood transfusion under any circumstances. This is against my faith.''\n\nHow do you approach this situation?"},{"step":2,"type":"history","title":"Assess Capacity","content":"You sit down with Margaret privately and calmly. She is alert and oriented. She clearly understands her condition, understands she may die without a transfusion, has weighed this against her religious beliefs, and is communicating her decision consistently.\n\nHer husband is outside and has approached nursing staff saying ''You must give her blood — she doesn''t know what she''s saying.''\n\nWhat do you establish about her capacity, and how do you handle the husband?"},{"step":3,"type":"examination","title":"Clinical Update","content":"Despite uterotonics and surgical haemostasis, Margaret''s Hb has dropped to 48 g/L. She is becoming tachycardic (HR 118) but remains conscious and lucid. She reiterates her refusal clearly.\n\nShe has a valid Advance Care Directive signed 6 months ago refusing blood products.\n\nWhat alternatives can you offer, and what are your obligations?"},{"step":4,"type":"investigations","title":"Team Discussion","content":"The obstetrics consultant suggests obtaining an urgent court order to override her refusal. A senior nurse says ''We have a duty of care — we should just transfuse her.''\n\nHow do you respond, and what is the medico-legally correct course of action?"},{"step":5,"type":"management","title":"Management Plan","content":"Outline your full management plan, including: alternatives to transfusion, your ethical and legal obligations, team communication, and how you document this situation.","model_answer":"1. RESPECT her refusal — she has demonstrated capacity and has a valid ACD\n2. A court order CANNOT override a competent adult''s refusal — do NOT pursue this\n3. Husband has NO legal authority to consent on her behalf while she has capacity\n4. Alternatives: IV iron, erythropoietin, tranexamic acid, cell salvage, normovolaemic haemodilution, surgical haemostasis optimisation\n5. Involve haematology for bloodless medicine advice\n6. Full documentation: capacity assessment, ACD sighted, discussions, alternatives offered\n7. Ethics committee — involve if ongoing team conflict\n8. Continue all other resuscitation measures (fluids, vasopressors, surgical intervention)\n9. Maintain respectful, non-judgemental communication with Margaret throughout\n10. Do not abandon her care — continue aggressive non-blood management"},{"step":6,"type":"debrief","title":"Debrief & Examiner Tips","content":"Key learning points:\n\n✅ A competent adult has an absolute right to refuse treatment, even life-saving treatment\n✅ Capacity is decision-specific — assess formally using the 4-component test\n✅ An Advance Care Directive is legally binding if valid and applicable\n✅ The husband (as next of kin) has NO authority to override a capacitous patient\n✅ The AMC examiner looks for: non-judgemental approach, correct legal framework, genuine exploration of alternatives\n\n⚠️ Common mistakes:\n- Trying to obtain a court order (incorrect — only applicable for patients WITHOUT capacity)\n- Deferring to the family instead of the patient\n- Abandoning care because of the refusal\n\nReference: AMC Good Medical Practice — Consent & Capacity (2023)"}]'
),
(
  'ECG Interpretation — Identify the Arrhythmia',
  'Procedural & Clinical Skills',
  'Medium',
  10,
  'CAT 1',
  '[{"step":1,"type":"presentation","title":"Clinical Context","content":"A 68-year-old woman presents to ED with palpitations and mild shortness of breath for 3 hours. BP 138/84, HR irregular at ~110 bpm, SpO2 97%.\n\nA 12-lead ECG is performed. Describe your systematic approach to interpreting this ECG."},{"step":2,"type":"history","title":"Systematic ECG Approach","content":"The systematic approach to any ECG:\n1. Rate — is it fast, slow or normal?\n2. Rhythm — regular or irregular? Is there a P wave before every QRS?\n3. Axis — normal, LAD, or RAD?\n4. P wave — morphology, duration\n5. PR interval — normal (120-200ms)?\n6. QRS — width (narrow <120ms vs broad ≥120ms)\n7. ST segment and T waves — elevation, depression, inversion?\n8. QT interval — prolonged?\n\nFindings on this ECG: Irregularly irregular rhythm, no discernible P waves, narrow QRS complexes, rate ~110 bpm, fibrillatory baseline.\n\nWhat is your diagnosis?"},{"step":3,"type":"examination","title":"Diagnosis Confirmed","content":"Diagnosis: Atrial Fibrillation with rapid ventricular response\n\nKey ECG features of AF:\n✅ Irregularly irregular rhythm (no two R-R intervals the same)\n✅ Absent P waves — replaced by chaotic fibrillatory baseline\n✅ Narrow QRS (unless aberrant conduction)\n✅ Ventricular rate variable — here ~110 bpm (rapid response)\n\nNow consider: Is this new-onset or known AF? Does she need rate control, rhythm control, or anticoagulation? What is her CHADS-VASc score?"},{"step":4,"type":"investigations","title":"Further Workup","content":"History reveals this is new-onset AF within 48 hours. No previous cardiac history. She is haemodynamically stable.\n\nCHADS-VASc score:\n- C: No CCF = 0\n- H: No hypertension = 0\n- A2: Age 68 = 1\n- D: No diabetes = 0\n- S2: No stroke = 0\n- V: No vascular disease = 0\n- A: Female sex = 1\nTotal = 2 → Anticoagulation recommended\n\nWhat is your management plan?"},{"step":5,"type":"management","title":"Management Plan","content":"She is haemodynamically stable with new-onset AF <48 hours. Outline your management covering: rate control, rhythm control options, anticoagulation strategy, and follow-up.","model_answer":"1. RATE CONTROL: Metoprolol 25-50mg oral (or IV if needed) — target HR <110 at rest\n2. RHYTHM CONTROL: Cardioversion within 48h is safe without TOE in new AF (<48h)\n   - Electrical cardioversion (DC) preferred if unstable — not the case here\n   - Pharmacological: flecainide (if no structural heart disease) or amiodarone\n3. ANTICOAGULATION: CHADS-VASc = 2 → start anticoagulation\n   - Preferred: DOAC (rivaroxaban or apixaban) over warfarin\n   - Start before cardioversion or at least 3 weeks prior if delayed\n4. INVESTIGATIONS: Echo (structural disease?), TFTs (thyroid AF), FBC, EUC, LFTs\n5. FOLLOW-UP: Cardiology referral, repeat ECG post-cardioversion, ongoing anticoagulation review\n6. EDUCATION: AF warning signs, stroke risk, medication compliance"},{"step":6,"type":"debrief","title":"Debrief & Examiner Tips","content":"Key learning points:\n\n✅ AF = irregularly irregular + absent P waves — the most common sustained arrhythmia\n✅ CHADS-VASc guides anticoagulation — score ≥2 in men or ≥3 in women → anticoagulate\n✅ New AF <48h: safe to cardiovert without TOE\n✅ DOACs preferred over warfarin in non-valvular AF\n✅ Always look for reversible causes: thyroid disease, infection, electrolyte imbalance\n\n⚠️ Common mistakes:\n- Anticoagulating after cardioversion but not before\n- Using rate control without considering rhythm control in new-onset AF\n- Missing the ''irregularly irregular'' pattern (vs regular tachycardia)\n\nReference: Oxford Handbook of Emergency Medicine — Arrhythmias (2024)"}]'
)
on conflict do nothing;
